<section xml:id="sec-kepII_law" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Derivation of Kepler's II Law</title>


  <image source ="triangle.png" width="50%"> </image>

  <p> 
    The small area of a given triangle 


    <md>
      <mrow> \,dA \amp  = \frac{1}{2}r\,dr\sin\phi </mrow> 
      <mrow> or, \quad \,d\vec{A} \amp = \frac{1}{2}(\vec{r} \times \,d\vec{r}) </mrow>
      <mrow> or, \quad \frac{\,d \vec{A}}{\,dt} \amp = \frac{1}{2}[\vec{r} \times \frac{\,d\vec{r}}{\,dt}] </mrow>
    </md>

        
   <men xml:id="eqn-kII1">
    \frac{\,d\vec{A}}{\,dt} = \frac{1}{2}[\vec{r} \times \vec{v}] 
   </men>
   
  But from angular momentum, we have 
  <me>
    \vec{L}=m(\vec{r}\times\vec{v})
  </me>
  Therefore <xref ref="eqn-kII1"/> can be written as 

  <me>
    \frac{\,d\vec{A}}{\,dt} =  \frac{\vec{L}}{2m} 
  </me>
  and 

  <me>
   or, \quad  \vec{\dot{A}} =  \frac{1}{2m}\vec{L} 
  </me>
  again, 

  <me>
   \vec{\ddot{A}} =  \frac{\,d}{\,dt}(\vec{\dot{A}}) = \frac{1}{2m}(\frac{\,d}{\,dt}\vec{L}) = 0
  </me>
  
  Since <m>L</m> is constant from conservation of angular momentum.
  
Therefore we can say 
<men xml:id="eqn-kII2">
  \vec{\dot{A}} = \frac{\,d\vec{A}}{\,dt} = \frac{\vec{L}}{2m}  = constant.
</men>
That is areal velocity of planet is constant. 
</p>
</section>